22 PART II. PROSTATE CANCER CONTROL PROGRAM
23 SECTION 2.1. There is appropriated from the General Fund to the Department of
24 Health and Human Services, Division of Public Health, the sum of two million dollars
25 ($2,000,000) in recurring funds for the 2026-2027 fiscal year to be used to establish and
26 administer a statewide Prostate Cancer Control Program that provides free or low-cost prostate
27 cancer screenings and follow-up to any man residing in North Carolina who meets all of the
28 following criteria:
29 (1) Is uninsured or underinsured.
30 (2) Is not a beneficiary of Medicare Part B or Medicaid.
31 (3) Is between 50 and 70 years of age and without a family history of prostate
32 cancer or is between 40 and 70 years of age with a family history of prostate
33 cancer. For the purpose of this subdivision, a man with a family history of
34 prostate cancer means any man with at least one first-degree relative who (i)
35 was diagnosed with prostate cancer, (ii) developed prostate cancer, (iii) died
36 as a result of prostate cancer, (iv) was diagnosed with a cancer known to be
37 associated with increased risk of prostate cancer, or (v) has a genetic alteration
38 known to be associated with increased risk of prostate cancer.
39 (4) Has a household income below two hundred fifty percent (250%) of the
40 federal poverty level.
41
42 PART III. HEALTH INSURANCE REGULATION CHANGES TO CREATE PARITY
43 FOR SUPPLEMENTAL AND DIAGNOSTIC BREAST IMAGING
44 SECTION 3.1.(a) G.S. 58-51-57 is recodified as G.S. 58-3-271.
45 SECTION 3.1.(b) G.S. 58-65-92 is repealed.
46 SECTION 3.1.(c) G.S. 58-67-76 is repealed.
47 SECTION 3.2. G.S. 58-3-271, as enacted by Section 3.1(a) of this act, reads as
48 rewritten:
49 "§ 58-3-271. Coverage for diagnostic, screening, and supplemental examinations for
50 breast cancer, including mammograms and other imaging, and cervical cancer
51 screening.
Page 4 DRH40688-MGa-155C

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (a) The following definitions apply in this section:
2 (1) Breast magnetic resonance imaging. – A diagnostic tool that uses a powerful
3 magnetic field, radio waves, and a computer to produce detailed pictures of
4 the structures within the breast.
5 (2) Breast ultrasound. – A noninvasive diagnostic tool that uses high-frequency
6 sound waves to produce detailed images of the breast.
7 (3) Cost-sharing. – A deductible, coinsurance, copayment, and any maximum
8 limitation on the application of a deductible, coinsurance, copayment, or
9 similar out-of-pocket expense.
10 (4) Diagnostic examination for breast cancer. – An examination for breast cancer
11 that is determined by the healthcare provider treating the patient to be
12 medically necessary and appropriate and that may include breast magnetic
13 resonance imaging, breast ultrasound, and diagnostic low-dose
14 mammography to evaluate the abnormality in the breast that meets one of the
15 following criteria:
16 a. Is seen or suspected from a screening examination for breast cancer.
17 b. Is detected by another means of examination.
18 (5) High-deductible health plan. – As defined under the Internal Revenue Code.
19 (6) Low-dose mammography. – A radiologic procedure for the early detection of
20 breast cancer using equipment dedicated specifically for mammography,
21 including a physician's interpretation of the results of the procedure.
22 (7) Screening examination for breast cancer. – Low-dose mammography, or an
23 equivalent procedure, that is used to determine if there is abnormality in the
24 breast.
25 (8) Screening of early detection of cervical cancer. – Examinations and laboratory
26 tests used to detect cervical cancer, including conventional PAP smear
27 screening, liquid-based cytology, and human papilloma virus (HPV) detection
28 methods for women with equivocal findings on cervical cytologic analysis
29 that are subject to the approval of and have been approved by the United States
30 Food and Drug Administration.
31 (9) Section 223. – Section 223 of the Internal Revenue Code or its equivalent.
32 (10) Supplemental examination for breast cancer. – An examination for breast
33 cancer that is determined by the healthcare provider treating the patient to be
34 medically necessary and appropriate and that may include breast magnetic
35 resonance imaging or breast ultrasound to screen for cancer when there is no
36 abnormality seen or suspected if the patient meets either of the following
37 criteria:
38 a. The patient is at increased risk for breast cancer based on the patient's
39 personal medical history or family medical history of breast cancer.
40 b. The patient has a breast cancer risk profile that qualifies the patient
41 based on current recommendations of the United States Preventive
42 Services Task Force, also known as USPSTF.
43 (a)(a1) Every policy or contract of accident or health insurance, and every preferred provider
44 benefit plan under G.S. 58-50-56, that is issued, renewed, or amended on or after January 1, 1992,
45 health benefit plan offered by an insurer in this State shall provide coverage for examinations
46 and laboratory tests for the screening for the early detection of cervical cancer and for low-dose
47 screening mammography. The same deductibles, coinsurance, and other limitations as apply to
48 similar services covered under the policy, contract, or plan shall apply to coverage for
49 examinations and laboratory tests for the screening for the early detection of cervical cancer and
50 low-dose screening mammography.
DRH40688-MGa-155C Page 5

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (a1) As used in this section, "examinations and laboratory tests for the screening for the
2 early detection of cervical cancer" means conventional PAP smear screening, liquid-based
3 cytology, and human papilloma virus (HPV) detection methods for women with equivocal
4 findings on cervical cytologic analysis that are subject to the approval of and have been approved
5 by the United States Food and Drug Administration.
6 (b) As used in this section, "low-dose screening mammography" means a radiologic
7 procedure for the early detection of breast cancer provided to an asymptomatic woman using
8 equipment dedicated specifically for mammography, including a physician's interpretation of the
9 results of the procedure.
10 (b1) Every health benefit plan offered by an insurer that provides benefits for a diagnostic
11 or supplemental examination for breast cancer shall ensure that the cost-sharing requirements
12 applicable to a diagnostic or supplemental examination for breast cancer are no less favorable
13 than the cost-sharing requirements applicable to low-dose screening mammography for breast
14 cancer.
15 (b2) An insurer shall not be required to reimburse a healthcare provider that is not a
16 contracted provider in the provider network of a health benefit plan offered by the insurer any
17 reimbursement rate more than the rate paid to a provider that has contracted with the insurer to
18 participate in the provider network of the health benefit plan for any of the following services:
19 (1) Diagnostic, screening, or supplemental examination for breast cancer.
20 (2) Low-dose mammography.
21 (3) Breast ultrasound.
22 (4) Breast magnetic resonance imaging.
23 (c) Coverage for low-dose screening mammography shall be provided as follows:
24 (1) One or more mammograms a year, as recommended by a physician, for any
25 woman who is at risk for breast cancer. For purposes of this subdivision, a
26 woman is at risk for breast cancer if any one or more of the following is true:
27 a. The woman has a personal history of breast cancer;cancer.
28 b. The woman has a personal history of biopsy-proven benign breast
29 disease;disease.
30 c. The woman's mother, sister, or daughter has or has had breast cancer;
31 orcancer.
32 d. The woman has not given birth prior to the age of 30;30.
33 (2) One baseline mammogram for any woman 35 through 39 years of age,
34 inclusive;inclusive.
35 (3) A mammogram every other year for any woman 40 through 49 years of age,
36 inclusive, or more frequently upon recommendation of a physician;
37 andphysician.
38 (4) A mammogram every year for any woman 50 years of age or older.
39 (d) Reimbursement for a mammogram authorized under this section shall be made only
40 if the facility in which the mammogram was performed meets mammography accreditation
41 standards established by the North Carolina Medical Care Commission.
42 (e) Coverage for the screening for the early detection of cervical cancer shall be in
43 accordance with the most recently published American Cancer Society American College of
44 Obstetricians and Gynecologists' guidelines or guidelines adopted by the North Carolina
45 Advisory Committee on Cancer Coordination and Control. Coverage shall include the
46 examination, the laboratory fee, and the physician's interpretation of the laboratory results.
47 Reimbursements for laboratory fees shall be made only if the laboratory meets accreditation
48 standards adopted by the North Carolina Medical Care Commission.
49 (f) If the application of any provision of this section would render the insured ineligible
50 for a health savings account under section 223, then that provision shall apply only for
51 high-deductible health plans with respect to the deductible of that plan after the insured has
